<h2>What are habits?
</h2>

<p>Habits are actions that we do without thinking, when we have a particular prompt or cure (Robbins & Costa, 2017). They are built up when we do they same thing, in the same way, to the point that it almost becomes instinctual and we do it automatically.
</p>

<p>When you get into certain habits it takes little to no thought, like with the habit of going home after work or school. You can end up back at home without remembering how you did it.
</p>

<p>Our habits can include all our daily behaviours that we do instinctually, both healthy and unhealthy, such as:
</p>

<ul>
    <li>the time we wake up and go to sleep
    </li>
    <li>how often we smoke or drink
    </li>
    <li>how much we might exercise
    </li>
    <li>when we shower and brush our teeth
    </li>
</ul>

<p>They can also include:
</p>

<ul>
    <li>what we think during the day, about ourselves and the world
    </li>
    <li>what we eat and drink (when, and how much)
    </li>
    <li>how we respond to people
    </li>
    <li>the work we do and how we do it
    </li>
    <li>what we do when we’re stressed, like bite our nails or touch our hair
    </li>
</ul>

<p>As the word says, habits are habitual, they make up a lot of what we do, and interestingly what we think. So they can play are very big part in our lives.
</p>

