<h2>Why do we have habits?
</h2>

<p>An interesting thing about our bodies is that they’ve evolved to be energy-efficient. Our minds have created shortcuts to help us process the world around us.
</p>

<p>Since the world is full of so much information, without these shortcuts, we’d be aware of so much information that we wouldn’t have the mental resources to get anything done.
</p>

<p>So we have a lot of shortcuts. Really, we have a lot of them. Blog here about some of our shortcuts
</p>

<p>Our habits are one such shortcut. They simplify our lives and make them easier, by removing our conscious thoughts, awareness and decision-making, freeing up more mental energy for other tasks.
</p>

<p>Take your journey to the shops. If you’ve moved somewhere new, or have to take a different route, it can take a bit of energy. You need to work out where you need to go, how to get there, which turns you need to take.
</p>

<p>But after a while, your brain knows where you are and where you’re going, all without you being aware of it. This can leave you energy to think about what you need to buy or to listen to a podcast.
</p>

<p>However, habits like these can sometimes be to our detriment. Ever left your home aiming for one place and ended up at work or a familiar place by accident? We can get so used to doing the same thing, that we’ll often default to it, whether or not that’s what we intended.
</p>

<p>By making the actions that we do over and over again quick, easy and and energy-efficient to do, our bodies make our lives easier. Our habits become effortless, an underlying current to our daily lives. But it’s important that the habits we have, help us.
</p>

