<h2>How our environment affects our habits
</h2>

<p>Changing our habits can be incredibly difficult, or incredibly easy, depending on your situation. One of the easiest ways to change our habits is to have external environmental encouragement, essentially to be in a situation where it pushes you into the habit.
</p>

<p>For example, if you go to school and live with parents who expect you to succeed, you’re more likely to get into habits like doing homework and going to bed on time. Your parents would create an environment that push you into going to school, studying
</p>

<p>In fact, any lifestyle that includes a schedule, prepared mealtimes, cleaning, and a community that expects you to succeed, will make habits easier, as the mental work to create new habits is reduced. Someone else makes the decision, you just need to follow their plan.
</p>

<p>These situations make our lives easier because someone is doing the work that we would normally have to do ourselves. This includes physical tasks like cooking meals, cleaning and tidying, but also mental work like figuring out what time to do things. Plus, when you take away the mental workload for planning, prepping and making food, as well as doing the cleaning and tidying up, it frees up a lot of our energy for other tasks.
</p>

<p>Unfortunately, these environments are either expensive to run, so most of us don’t have the luxury of living in them, or require us to give up certain freedoms.
</p>

<p>But don’t despair, we can still create better habits in non-ideal situations, it just requires a bit of energy and a lot of clever tricks. Luckily, I’ve sorted through these to help both of us. We can do this!
</p>

