<h2>Why it is so difficult to change habits
</h2>

<p>Often, our habits have a pay-off or feel-good factor for doing them (otherwise why would we do them?). Some of these rewards are healthy, like with brushing your teeth. The reward is feeling clean, having better breath, and feeling like you have your life together. All good stuff.
</p>

<p>But our unhealthy habits have a pay-off too. Food and drink like chocolate, crisps or alcohol makes us feel good in a number of ways. We get a pay-off from tasting something we enjoy, they’re often comforting, and remind us of good times. 
</p>

<p>The same goes for going on social media, as well as playing games. They give us a grief rise in “happy-hormones”, which keeps us going back.
</p>

<p>Once we have built up a habit often enough, we will gravitate towards it because we expect to do it and get the good-feeling. In fact, we can become so focused on getting that good feeling that if we don’t get it, we aren’t able to focus on anything else.
</p>

<p>This is why it can be so difficult to give up bad habits. Habits where the good feeling is inconsistent are the most difficult to give up. Social media is a key example of this. We scroll until we see something we like that satisfies us. But this could be after 30 seconds or 2 hours, making it difficult for us to give it up.
</p>

